@flexiarg enrichment/rational-reconstruction
@title Rational Reconstruction Over Bulk Import
@sigils [日/引]
@keywords rational, reconstruction, replay, bitemporal, incremental, correction, history, provenance
@audience futon developers, enrichment operators, methodology designers
@tone analytic-foundational
@factor Keen investigation (dhammavicaya)
@references [realtime/learn-as-you-go iching/hexagram-53-jian enrichment/ARGUMENT enrichment/layer-as-evidence]

! conclusion:
  Build the codebase's self-representation through layered rational
  reconstruction — replaying enrichment as if discipline had been maintained
  all along — rather than a one-shot static analysis dump.

  + context: The futon stack has 5+ years of development history across 8+
    repos. A bulk static analysis could produce a comprehensive snapshot, but
    it would have no provenance (when was this edge discovered?), no
    correction trail (which early assumptions were wrong?), and no
    transferable methodology (how would someone else do this for their
    codebase?).
  + IF:
    We want enrichment that is replayable, correctable, and transferable
    to other codebases.
  + HOWEVER:
    Rational reconstruction is slower than bulk import — each layer must be
    verified before the next begins, and corrections between layers require
    additional ingestion runs.
  + THEN:
    Structure enrichment as numbered layers (L0-L5), each a timestamped
    batch of hyperedges with its own evidence entry. XTDB bitemporality
    makes each layer queryable as-of its ingestion time. Corrections in
    later layers supersede but don't erase earlier layers. The growth of
    understanding is itself navigable.
  + BECAUSE:
    Three advantages compound:
    (1) REPLAYABILITY — "what did we know about futon3c.peripheral as of
    layer 3?" is answerable via bitemporal query. This is impossible with
    a one-shot dump.
    (2) INCREMENTAL CORRECTION — early layers WILL have errors (orphan
    namespaces that are actually entry points, churn spikes from mass
    renames). Later layers fix them. The correction history shows where
    the codebase's self-image was wrong — itself valuable knowledge.
    (3) METHODOLOGY TRANSFER — the discipline of "enrich incrementally,
    record what you find, correct as you go" is the discipline we'd want
    any team to adopt. Building it on our own code first validates the
    process. The learn-as-you-go [日] pattern ensures each layer captures
    not just findings but surprises and learnings.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - evidence: Layer 0 run with meta/enrichment-layer record
    - evidence: Layer 1 run that corrects at least one Layer 0 anomaly
    - evidence: bitemporal query showing enrichment growth between layers
    - falsifying-observation: if Layer 0→L1 correction rate is < 5%, the
      rational reconstruction overhead may not justify itself over bulk
      import — reassess at that point.
